00:00:25.460 --> 00:00:31.690
PROFESSOR: Today I want to walk
through that case in quotes.

00:00:31.690 --> 00:00:33.430
It's more of a teaching
note than a case,

00:00:33.430 --> 00:00:38.140
but there are some questions
to talk about and let

00:00:38.140 --> 00:00:41.170
me pose one that probably
occurred to some of you

00:00:41.170 --> 00:00:43.930
as you began reading the
course-- reading that case.

00:00:43.930 --> 00:00:48.250
Why are we talking about EPA at
the front of a case on energy?

00:00:50.870 --> 00:00:53.530
Sam?

00:00:53.530 --> 00:00:54.485
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE].

00:00:54.485 --> 00:00:56.890
But especially it
can depends a lot

00:00:56.890 --> 00:00:58.330
on where your energy comes from.

00:00:58.330 --> 00:00:59.747
Like, [INAUDIBLE]
talked about how

00:00:59.747 --> 00:01:02.140
the coal causes like a
lot of more [INAUDIBLE]

00:01:02.140 --> 00:01:03.640
than [INAUDIBLE].

00:01:03.640 --> 00:01:05.190
PROFESSOR: So on
the one hand energy,

00:01:05.190 --> 00:01:07.065
Energy is the source of
the kind of pollution

00:01:07.065 --> 00:01:10.350
EPA was created to deal
with, and on the other hand--

00:01:10.350 --> 00:01:14.698
STUDENT: Also the different
regulations impact [INAUDIBLE]

00:01:14.698 --> 00:01:17.950
deductions [INAUDIBLE].

00:01:17.950 --> 00:01:19.970
PROFESSOR: So a lot
of energy policy

00:01:19.970 --> 00:01:24.185
is made in under the umbrella
of environmental policy.

00:01:27.600 --> 00:01:30.570
Plus or minus coal is not
going to be about coal,

00:01:30.570 --> 00:01:32.687
but it's going to be about--

00:01:32.687 --> 00:01:34.020
or not going to be about energy.

00:01:34.020 --> 00:01:36.585
It's going to be
about the environment.

00:01:36.585 --> 00:01:37.710
Let me call your attention.

00:01:37.710 --> 00:01:42.720
This was an optional reading
but the National Academy

00:01:42.720 --> 00:01:47.430
of Sciences unpriced
consequences paper is probably

00:01:47.430 --> 00:01:53.040
the best recent summary
of this literature,

00:01:53.040 --> 00:01:57.460
and it talks about putting
climate to one side.

00:01:57.460 --> 00:01:58.990
We'll come back to that.

00:01:58.990 --> 00:02:05.200
It credits coal-fired power
plants in 2005 with $62 billion

00:02:05.200 --> 00:02:07.780
worth of damages--

00:02:07.780 --> 00:02:10.750
externalities,
unpriced consequences

00:02:10.750 --> 00:02:15.820
with a huge range per
kilowatt hour in the damages

00:02:15.820 --> 00:02:18.430
caused by individual plants.

00:02:18.430 --> 00:02:22.480
Natural gas fired power
plants, much less in aggregate

00:02:22.480 --> 00:02:27.910
and, in fact, much less, except
for a few cases, per plant.

00:02:27.910 --> 00:02:32.500
Transportation, both light
duty, cars and light trucks,

00:02:32.500 --> 00:02:35.260
and heavy duty, heavy
trucks and equipment,

00:02:35.260 --> 00:02:37.510
add up to about $56 billion.

00:02:37.510 --> 00:02:40.030
Not that far off--

00:02:40.030 --> 00:02:43.895
not that far off
coal-fired power plants.

00:02:43.895 --> 00:02:46.270
The other interesting thing--
and we'll come back to this

00:02:46.270 --> 00:02:48.340
later later today--

00:02:48.340 --> 00:02:50.860
there's a little-- there's a
parenthetical assessment where

00:02:50.860 --> 00:02:53.230
they say-- where they
look at alternative forms

00:02:53.230 --> 00:02:57.910
of transportation alternative
power trains for cars,

00:02:57.910 --> 00:03:00.910
and they conclude that electric
vehicles are much worse--

00:03:00.910 --> 00:03:03.220
not much worse--
worse environmentally

00:03:03.220 --> 00:03:07.300
than diesel, which, in turn, is
worse than gasoline or ethanol.

00:03:07.300 --> 00:03:10.420
And the reason is, of
course, electric vehicles

00:03:10.420 --> 00:03:14.550
across the country
are half coal-powered,

00:03:14.550 --> 00:03:17.050
because that's where the
electricity comes from.

00:03:17.050 --> 00:03:21.360
And this, sort of, gets
lost in the discussion.

00:03:21.360 --> 00:03:23.130
But there are these numbers.

00:03:25.720 --> 00:03:27.400
Where do they come from?

00:03:27.400 --> 00:03:29.910
Where do you think they
come from? $62 billion

00:03:29.910 --> 00:03:31.620
is not peeling paint.

00:03:31.620 --> 00:03:37.890
$62 billion is mostly valuing
premature mortality, i.e.

00:03:37.890 --> 00:03:40.430
people die.

00:03:40.430 --> 00:03:42.690
There's a little bit
of health effects.

00:03:42.690 --> 00:03:44.520
People get bronchitis.

00:03:44.520 --> 00:03:50.280
But mostly, those numbers
are from people dying.

00:03:50.280 --> 00:03:51.880
How would you do that?

00:03:51.880 --> 00:03:53.880
Does it make sense to
compute numbers like that?

00:03:53.880 --> 00:03:55.880
Does is it makes sense
to use numbers like that?

00:03:55.880 --> 00:03:57.520
How would you use
numbers like that?

00:03:57.520 --> 00:04:00.370
Do you believe
numbers like that?

00:04:00.370 --> 00:04:02.920
People say $62 billion
worth of damages.

00:04:07.170 --> 00:04:11.760
Putting a price on human
life, putting a price on risk,

00:04:11.760 --> 00:04:13.560
what do you think?

00:04:13.560 --> 00:04:15.450
You read that,
what's your reaction?

00:04:15.450 --> 00:04:17.130
How about a reaction?

00:04:17.130 --> 00:04:19.269
Max, you've got a reaction?

00:04:19.269 --> 00:04:22.960
STUDENT: Probably the cost of
medical expenses associated.

00:04:22.960 --> 00:04:24.460
PROFESSOR: That be
one way to do it,

00:04:24.460 --> 00:04:27.570
but that's not usually
how they do it.

00:04:27.570 --> 00:04:29.310
See one of the--

00:04:29.310 --> 00:04:32.400
if you do that, you can
come to the conclusion

00:04:32.400 --> 00:04:34.980
that cigarette
smoking is terrific,

00:04:34.980 --> 00:04:38.820
because people die at a
younger age if they smoke,

00:04:38.820 --> 00:04:44.825
and therefore they don't have
the long care costs of people

00:04:44.825 --> 00:04:46.200
in their 80s or
90s, because they

00:04:46.200 --> 00:04:47.970
don't get to their 80s or 90s.

00:04:47.970 --> 00:04:54.030
So you can measure costs of
sickness sometimes that way

00:04:54.030 --> 00:04:56.010
but not death, not death.

00:04:56.010 --> 00:04:57.270
Anybody else?

00:04:57.270 --> 00:04:59.070
Julian?

00:04:59.070 --> 00:05:02.204
STUDENT: What would be their
contribution to the GDP

00:05:02.204 --> 00:05:06.222
and their economic
contribution is [INAUDIBLE]..

00:05:06.222 --> 00:05:07.680
PROFESSOR: That's
one way to do it.

00:05:07.680 --> 00:05:10.050
Do you like that?

00:05:10.050 --> 00:05:12.018
You could do it that way.

00:05:12.018 --> 00:05:15.520
STUDENT: I would try and take
all their economic impact,

00:05:15.520 --> 00:05:20.490
including the health costs,
their [INAUDIBLE] of tax base,

00:05:20.490 --> 00:05:24.270
but how much they cost in taxes.

00:05:24.270 --> 00:05:27.750
PROFESSOR: So basically
retired people--

00:05:27.750 --> 00:05:31.140
and this is beginning to
beginning to bother me--

00:05:31.140 --> 00:05:34.320
retired people should have
a negative value, right?

00:05:34.320 --> 00:05:36.600
Because they're drawing
down social security.

00:05:36.600 --> 00:05:38.490
They're drawing down Medicare.

00:05:38.490 --> 00:05:40.470
They're not working.

00:05:40.470 --> 00:05:42.300
Just gone.

00:05:42.300 --> 00:05:47.400
So that method has been used.

00:05:47.400 --> 00:05:50.250
It does have that
consequence I just described.

00:05:50.250 --> 00:05:52.530
But for working age people--

00:05:52.530 --> 00:05:56.700
and sometimes that's
done in court cases.

00:05:56.700 --> 00:06:02.160
So someone is killed by
negligence and you sue.

00:06:02.160 --> 00:06:03.250
And what do you get?

00:06:03.250 --> 00:06:07.200
Well, one way that
sometimes calculated

00:06:07.200 --> 00:06:10.980
is, well, how much money would--

00:06:10.980 --> 00:06:11.730
the wife sues.

00:06:11.730 --> 00:06:13.560
The husband was killed at work.

00:06:13.560 --> 00:06:17.850
The wife gets the husband's
expected lifetime earnings.

00:06:17.850 --> 00:06:20.130
That isn't what they do
here because a lot of this

00:06:20.130 --> 00:06:23.850
is mortality of
older people, and you

00:06:23.850 --> 00:06:26.160
don't want to come up
with a negative number.

00:06:26.160 --> 00:06:27.690
The way they do it--

00:06:27.690 --> 00:06:30.150
because it's a little
bit of a little bit

00:06:30.150 --> 00:06:34.654
of a puzzle-- the way they
do it is they look at,

00:06:34.654 --> 00:06:43.800
at least recently, you look at
weight premiums for risky jobs.

00:06:43.800 --> 00:06:46.920
So you say, how
much more does it

00:06:46.920 --> 00:06:50.880
take to persuade somebody to
be a welder underwater, which

00:06:50.880 --> 00:06:55.290
is a bit hazardous than
they'd be a welder on land.

00:06:55.290 --> 00:06:59.400
And a number of
calculations like that.

00:06:59.400 --> 00:07:03.870
Because you're not actually
valuing a death when you do

00:07:03.870 --> 00:07:04.590
these studies.

00:07:04.590 --> 00:07:07.290
You're valuing an
increase in risk.

00:07:07.290 --> 00:07:10.310
So you increase
the risk of death.

00:07:10.310 --> 00:07:13.310
And you say, all right,
well, in the marketplace,

00:07:13.310 --> 00:07:14.840
what are people willing--

00:07:14.840 --> 00:07:16.340
what does it
require, what do you

00:07:16.340 --> 00:07:19.370
have to pay people to get them
to assume an increased risk

00:07:19.370 --> 00:07:22.340
of death in certain settings?

00:07:22.340 --> 00:07:26.090
And then you play with that for
a while, make some assumptions,

00:07:26.090 --> 00:07:31.910
roll it around, and say the
value of a premature death

00:07:31.910 --> 00:07:36.140
$6 million, which is a
round number that's used.

00:07:36.140 --> 00:07:39.590
And then you say, OK.

00:07:39.590 --> 00:07:42.020
We look at how many
people we expect

00:07:42.020 --> 00:07:45.560
will die early because
of small particulates

00:07:45.560 --> 00:07:48.140
from coal-fired power plants.

00:07:48.140 --> 00:07:51.470
And we value that at
$6 million apiece.

00:07:51.470 --> 00:07:54.530
So you're not valuing a death
so much as you're valuing

00:07:54.530 --> 00:07:56.610
an increased risk of death.

00:07:56.610 --> 00:07:59.870
So that's how you do it.

00:07:59.870 --> 00:08:04.670
Should you use numbers like
that to make decisions?

00:08:04.670 --> 00:08:07.430
There were some readings
on whether cost benefit

00:08:07.430 --> 00:08:08.660
analysis is ethical.

00:08:08.660 --> 00:08:13.090
And some of it comes to that.

00:08:13.090 --> 00:08:16.040
STUDENT: The person [INAUDIBLE]
not really [INAUDIBLE]..

00:08:16.040 --> 00:08:19.770
I wouldn't place to much
attention on the very specific,

00:08:19.770 --> 00:08:21.120
value, per se.

00:08:21.120 --> 00:08:23.540
Maybe it would be--
for me, at least--

00:08:23.540 --> 00:08:29.060
it would be like relatively-- so
the same basic assumptions made

00:08:29.060 --> 00:08:32.270
for any different source,
maybe coal or natural gas.

00:08:32.270 --> 00:08:35.590
Maybe we see these
values relative.

00:08:35.590 --> 00:08:40.010
So it's much higher for coal
than for natural gas, just

00:08:40.010 --> 00:08:41.520
given the case between the two.

00:08:41.520 --> 00:08:44.570
But I wouldn't do a whole
analysis saying, OK, $6 million

00:08:44.570 --> 00:08:46.430
here and $6 million there.

00:08:46.430 --> 00:08:48.320
They could get cancer,
to OK, I mean--

00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:50.330
PROFESSOR: But you
got to know something

00:08:50.330 --> 00:08:53.300
about not just
relative, but absolute,

00:08:53.300 --> 00:08:55.250
to know whether it matters.

00:08:55.250 --> 00:08:59.840
If I told you the damages were
$5 from coal-fired power plants

00:08:59.840 --> 00:09:05.380
and $0.35 from gas-fired, that
wouldn't affect any decisions.

00:09:05.380 --> 00:09:12.050
If I told you it was $500
billion versus $200 million,

00:09:12.050 --> 00:09:14.190
that would drive a decision.

00:09:14.190 --> 00:09:17.660
So I take your point,
but sometimes you've

00:09:17.660 --> 00:09:19.593
got to have a sense
of the absolute,

00:09:19.593 --> 00:09:20.510
not just the relative.

00:09:20.510 --> 00:09:21.985
STUDENT: May I ask--

00:09:21.985 --> 00:09:22.860
PROFESSOR: Of course.

00:09:22.860 --> 00:09:26.510
STUDENT: --is there any
sense at least of error,

00:09:26.510 --> 00:09:30.290
or a band number of these--

00:09:30.290 --> 00:09:32.180
PROFESSOR: Oh, yeah.

00:09:32.180 --> 00:09:38.960
I mean, all this stuff
is subject to error.

00:09:38.960 --> 00:09:41.300
Take coal fired-power plants.

00:09:41.300 --> 00:09:42.920
Take a particular plant.

00:09:42.920 --> 00:09:47.870
First thing you're doing
is you're estimating where

00:09:47.870 --> 00:09:50.330
the stuff from that plant goes.

00:09:50.330 --> 00:09:54.930
OK, so that's a transport
model of one kind or another,

00:09:54.930 --> 00:09:58.400
which is averaging over a
bunch of weather conditions.

00:09:58.400 --> 00:09:59.780
And then you're using--

00:09:59.780 --> 00:10:05.060
and there's error there, because
you can't measure that well--

00:10:05.060 --> 00:10:08.990
and then you're using a
dose response curve based

00:10:08.990 --> 00:10:11.780
on a number of different
kinds of studies

00:10:11.780 --> 00:10:15.380
to say, if this
area gets this kind

00:10:15.380 --> 00:10:18.682
of particulate concentration
over this period of time-- oh,

00:10:18.682 --> 00:10:21.140
by the way, how much time do
people spend outside breathing

00:10:21.140 --> 00:10:23.480
it versus inside?

00:10:23.480 --> 00:10:25.130
Et cetera, et cetera.

00:10:25.130 --> 00:10:28.970
Then we would expect this
increase in the risk of death

00:10:28.970 --> 00:10:30.640
for people in this age bracket.

00:10:33.230 --> 00:10:34.520
Sure, there are error bars.

00:10:34.520 --> 00:10:38.510
You don't see them, but there
are pretty good size error

00:10:38.510 --> 00:10:39.150
bars.

00:10:39.150 --> 00:10:41.690
In fact, critics say they're
very wide error bars.

00:10:41.690 --> 00:10:43.460
And similarly, the
human life, even

00:10:43.460 --> 00:10:50.060
the people who do
this stuff, you're

00:10:50.060 --> 00:10:56.670
comparing a risk voluntarily
assumed with a risk imposed.

00:10:56.670 --> 00:11:00.680
How many of you
ride motorcycles?

00:11:00.680 --> 00:11:03.590
How many of you ridden
on a motorcycle?

00:11:03.590 --> 00:11:05.090
This is a risky activity.

00:11:05.090 --> 00:11:07.820
This increased your probability
of death significantly.

00:11:07.820 --> 00:11:09.650
You didn't think about it.

00:11:09.650 --> 00:11:11.240
If I told you,
however, we were going

00:11:11.240 --> 00:11:14.690
to pump poisonous gas into your
room that had the same effect,

00:11:14.690 --> 00:11:16.670
you'd go crazy.

00:11:16.670 --> 00:11:19.610
People distinguish between
risks they choose to assume

00:11:19.610 --> 00:11:20.900
and risks that are imposed.

00:11:20.900 --> 00:11:22.970
And I don't know
how to value that.

00:11:22.970 --> 00:11:24.290
So you had a comment?

00:11:24.290 --> 00:11:25.070
Yeah.

00:11:25.070 --> 00:11:27.320
STUDENT: I think this is
useful for bringing attention

00:11:27.320 --> 00:11:30.700
to an issue, rather than
the decision-making.

00:11:30.700 --> 00:11:32.650
Because when you
come to policymakers,

00:11:32.650 --> 00:11:38.375
they want a number that they
can associate with the issue.

00:11:38.375 --> 00:11:39.750
PROFESSOR: Actually,
policymakers

00:11:39.750 --> 00:11:43.410
tend to hate this
stuff because there

00:11:43.410 --> 00:11:45.510
is this value in
human life aspect.

00:11:45.510 --> 00:11:49.254
STUDENT: But when you go
through all the different steps.

00:11:49.254 --> 00:11:51.895
You go through all the
inputs, all the assumptions.

00:11:51.895 --> 00:11:53.520
They don't want to
go through all that.

00:11:53.520 --> 00:11:56.650
They want to compare numbers.

00:11:56.650 --> 00:11:58.390
PROFESSOR: Well,
we'll see in a second.

00:12:03.430 --> 00:12:05.860
Distinguish different
kinds of policymakers.

00:12:05.860 --> 00:12:07.690
But people who are
looking for votes

00:12:07.690 --> 00:12:10.180
do not like to say a human
life is worth $6 million

00:12:10.180 --> 00:12:13.240
or say anything that
sounds like a human life is

00:12:13.240 --> 00:12:16.030
worth $6 million,
because it's priceless.

00:12:16.030 --> 00:12:17.620
Saying it's priceless
doesn't get you

00:12:17.620 --> 00:12:21.520
a decision unless you can make
some other assumptions, which

00:12:21.520 --> 00:12:22.954
they did.

00:12:22.954 --> 00:12:24.835
STUDENT: Well, when
they use that number,

00:12:24.835 --> 00:12:28.260
they don't publicize the
fact that it is [INAUDIBLE]..

00:12:28.260 --> 00:12:33.430
PROFESSOR: I mean, every
presidential administration

00:12:33.430 --> 00:12:36.220
since, depending on how you
think about it, Carter--

00:12:36.220 --> 00:12:37.960
but certainly since Reagan--

00:12:37.960 --> 00:12:41.570
Republicans and Democrats have
done this kind of analysis

00:12:41.570 --> 00:12:42.070
quietly.

00:12:46.550 --> 00:12:48.970
OK, anything else?

00:12:48.970 --> 00:12:49.470
Yes.

00:12:49.470 --> 00:12:51.887
STUDENT: I had a quick question
about the electric vehicle

00:12:51.887 --> 00:12:52.570
statistic.

00:12:52.570 --> 00:12:52.930
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:12:52.930 --> 00:12:55.305
STUDENT: Is that based on
electric vehicles that are only

00:12:55.305 --> 00:12:56.650
run of coal-fired plants?

00:12:56.650 --> 00:12:57.730
Or is that--

00:12:57.730 --> 00:13:00.310
PROFESSOR: Assume the average
generation mix, I think.

00:13:00.310 --> 00:13:01.450
You can go back and check.

00:13:01.450 --> 00:13:03.160
But I think that's
what it said--

00:13:03.160 --> 00:13:05.080
that assuming the average
mix, which gets you

00:13:05.080 --> 00:13:07.270
about half coal ballpark.

00:13:07.270 --> 00:13:07.810
Yeah?

00:13:07.810 --> 00:13:10.090
STUDENT: Just to confirm,
they did not price carbon--

00:13:10.090 --> 00:13:11.170
PROFESSOR: Correct.

00:13:11.170 --> 00:13:12.500
Not in those, they didn't.

00:13:12.500 --> 00:13:15.220
There's a discussion--
again, you can look at it--

00:13:15.220 --> 00:13:21.250
of relative carbon
emissions, right?

00:13:21.250 --> 00:13:25.780
And coal gives you about
twice per kilowatt hour

00:13:25.780 --> 00:13:28.880
what gas gives you in
terms of carbon emissions.

00:13:28.880 --> 00:13:30.970
And they talk a little
bit about transportation.

00:13:33.653 --> 00:13:34.570
Now, I guess we won't.

00:13:34.570 --> 00:13:37.112
I was going to say we will come
to some discussion of pricing

00:13:37.112 --> 00:13:38.270
carbon.

00:13:38.270 --> 00:13:42.250
The Obama administration
has an official value

00:13:42.250 --> 00:13:45.820
for carbon emissions that it
uses for internal decisions.

00:13:49.880 --> 00:13:51.950
It sounds like a
reasonable number,

00:13:51.950 --> 00:13:55.100
but it rests on weak
foundations because--

00:13:55.100 --> 00:13:57.440
we'll talk about
this, but trying

00:13:57.440 --> 00:14:01.340
to understand the magnitude of
climate damages in a century

00:14:01.340 --> 00:14:05.510
and discounting it back
is a difficult exercise.

00:14:05.510 --> 00:14:08.000
OK.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:10.390
Let me move along.

00:14:10.390 --> 00:14:17.090
I want to talk about this
property rights analysis

00:14:17.090 --> 00:14:21.590
because I think it's
useful to think about.

00:14:21.590 --> 00:14:26.840
There are those people who
actually said that where

00:14:26.840 --> 00:14:30.740
you really don't need this kind
of government interference.

00:14:30.740 --> 00:14:37.010
You could just assign property
rights to either, say,

00:14:37.010 --> 00:14:39.830
clean air or clean
water, or property

00:14:39.830 --> 00:14:44.270
rights to dump pollution and
let the market sort it out.

00:14:44.270 --> 00:14:46.520
This is the so-called
Coase theorem.

00:14:52.050 --> 00:14:57.810
And the example that's given in
the Viscusi et cetera reading

00:14:57.810 --> 00:14:59.070
is this one.

00:14:59.070 --> 00:15:02.318
You have a mill.

00:15:02.318 --> 00:15:04.400
You have a river.

00:15:07.407 --> 00:15:08.240
And you have a town.

00:15:12.530 --> 00:15:15.020
The mill dumps pollution
into the river.

00:15:15.020 --> 00:15:18.320
The town takes water
out of the river.

00:15:18.320 --> 00:15:21.710
There's $500 worth of damage.

00:15:21.710 --> 00:15:26.900
OK, so drinking
the polluted water

00:15:26.900 --> 00:15:29.450
or using it to wash
clothes or whatever

00:15:29.450 --> 00:15:32.030
causes $500 worth of damages.

00:15:32.030 --> 00:15:36.530
The mill could clean
it up for $100.

00:15:36.530 --> 00:15:44.000
The town could treat
the water for $300.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:46.880
The argument goes, there
is no problem here.

00:15:46.880 --> 00:15:50.300
We just need to assign
property rights.

00:15:50.300 --> 00:15:56.000
Suppose you say that the town
is entitled to clean water.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:57.860
The town is entitled
to clean water.

00:15:57.860 --> 00:16:01.190
The town takes legal
action against the mill.

00:16:01.190 --> 00:16:03.980
The mill spends
$100 and cleans up.

00:16:03.980 --> 00:16:05.870
Simple.

00:16:05.870 --> 00:16:10.250
Suppose the mill is
entitled to pollute.

00:16:10.250 --> 00:16:12.560
Give them the property right.

00:16:12.560 --> 00:16:15.110
Then what happens?

00:16:15.110 --> 00:16:18.830
The town could
clean up for $300.

00:16:18.830 --> 00:16:21.500
But what would most likely
happen is they go to the mill

00:16:21.500 --> 00:16:25.070
and say, look, we'll pay
you something over $100

00:16:25.070 --> 00:16:25.760
to clean up.

00:16:25.760 --> 00:16:29.385
Something between $100-300.

00:16:29.385 --> 00:16:31.010
You're going to pay
them more than $300

00:16:31.010 --> 00:16:32.385
because you could
do it yourself.

00:16:32.385 --> 00:16:34.280
They're not going to
take less than $100.

00:16:34.280 --> 00:16:36.620
So there's some bargaining room.

00:16:36.620 --> 00:16:39.380
You're going to get rid
of the damages either way

00:16:39.380 --> 00:16:42.860
because it's cheaper to get
rid of them than to bear them.

00:16:42.860 --> 00:16:46.940
And either way, what happens
is the mill cleans up.

00:16:46.940 --> 00:16:50.180
In one case, the mill pays.

00:16:50.180 --> 00:16:52.340
In the other case,
the town pays.

00:16:52.340 --> 00:16:54.293
But in both cases,
the mill cleans up,

00:16:54.293 --> 00:16:56.210
the pollution goes away,
and all you had to do

00:16:56.210 --> 00:16:59.090
is assign property rights.

00:16:59.090 --> 00:17:03.942
So first of all, are there
questions about that?

00:17:03.942 --> 00:17:05.359
Does that make
that little example

00:17:05.359 --> 00:17:07.040
makes sense in its own terms?

00:17:10.410 --> 00:17:11.050
Yeah?

00:17:11.050 --> 00:17:12.545
STUDENT: What does
the mill need-

00:17:12.545 --> 00:17:13.920
like, the mill is
polluting, then

00:17:13.920 --> 00:17:16.087
they're sort of claiming
those rights anyway, right?

00:17:16.087 --> 00:17:17.329
So then--

00:17:17.329 --> 00:17:20.420
PROFESSOR: Well, we have that
happen at the outset, and then

00:17:20.420 --> 00:17:23.243
we and then we establish
property rights.

00:17:23.243 --> 00:17:24.660
Then we establish
property rights.

00:17:24.660 --> 00:17:28.310
So this is the status quo
before we put the law in effect,

00:17:28.310 --> 00:17:32.240
and what the law says is instead
of yelling at each other,

00:17:32.240 --> 00:17:34.760
one of you has the
right to enforce action

00:17:34.760 --> 00:17:36.740
against the other in court.

00:17:36.740 --> 00:17:41.030
So either the town can
force the mill to clean up

00:17:41.030 --> 00:17:44.090
or the mill can do
whatever it wants

00:17:44.090 --> 00:17:47.540
unless it's bribed or paid.

00:17:47.540 --> 00:17:50.540
So we start out with a situation
in which there are no property

00:17:50.540 --> 00:17:51.620
rights.

00:17:51.620 --> 00:17:53.780
The mill is polluting,
the town is complaining.

00:17:53.780 --> 00:17:55.640
We assign property
rights, the problem

00:17:55.640 --> 00:17:58.200
gets solved, is the argument.

00:17:58.200 --> 00:18:01.000
Either way, we assign them.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:03.610
STUDENT: Are property rights
necessary for the town

00:18:03.610 --> 00:18:06.300
to clean up the water?

00:18:06.300 --> 00:18:09.420
Because [INAUDIBLE] river
and they want water.

00:18:09.420 --> 00:18:13.090
PROFESSOR: Well, if the town--

00:18:13.090 --> 00:18:20.510
I mean, you could imagine
what property rights determine

00:18:20.510 --> 00:18:26.240
here is who pays, basically.

00:18:26.240 --> 00:18:30.350
Because if the-- which thing
is, if you don't have property

00:18:30.350 --> 00:18:34.580
rights, the town's going to
go up here and try to bargain.

00:18:34.580 --> 00:18:36.560
Because you're
saying, implicitly,

00:18:36.560 --> 00:18:40.017
unless you do something,
the mill just pollutes.

00:18:40.017 --> 00:18:42.350
Well, that's equivalent to
saying the mill has the right

00:18:42.350 --> 00:18:44.150
to pollute.

00:18:44.150 --> 00:18:47.210
If the mill has the
right to pollute,

00:18:47.210 --> 00:18:50.240
then the town is going to
have to pay them not to.

00:18:50.240 --> 00:18:53.540
If the town has the
right to clean water,

00:18:53.540 --> 00:18:55.910
then the mill is either going
to have to clean up or pay

00:18:55.910 --> 00:18:57.110
the town to clean up.

00:18:57.110 --> 00:18:58.640
It's cheaper for the mill.

00:18:58.640 --> 00:19:00.600
The mill cleans up.

00:19:00.600 --> 00:19:05.120
So if you say the mill
is just going to pollute,

00:19:05.120 --> 00:19:07.610
not if the town can stop it.

00:19:07.610 --> 00:19:09.500
Not if the town can stop it.

00:19:09.500 --> 00:19:14.030
That comes to the next
question, is why won't it work?

00:19:14.030 --> 00:19:18.050
One way one reason it might
not work in a real life case

00:19:18.050 --> 00:19:22.430
is the town doesn't
happen to have chemists

00:19:22.430 --> 00:19:25.070
and doesn't realize
that the water is dirty.

00:19:25.070 --> 00:19:27.590
So you might want to say,
gee, a role of government

00:19:27.590 --> 00:19:30.440
is to do some science
here, at least,

00:19:30.440 --> 00:19:35.060
and figure out what's going on
to do the studies of damages.

00:19:35.060 --> 00:19:36.860
And I want to make
sure everybody's

00:19:36.860 --> 00:19:41.902
got the example before
we go to run down

00:19:41.902 --> 00:19:42.860
this list a little bit.

00:19:42.860 --> 00:19:44.020
But are you on the example?

00:19:44.020 --> 00:19:46.550
Or are you on why
it might not work?

00:19:46.550 --> 00:19:49.610
STUDENT: I'm on the
example I was wondering,

00:19:49.610 --> 00:19:53.270
how do you decide who
gets the property right?

00:19:53.270 --> 00:19:56.630
PROFESSOR: Coase's point
is it doesn't matter.

00:19:56.630 --> 00:19:59.210
I mean, it matters from the
point of view of fairness,

00:19:59.210 --> 00:20:00.290
maybe.

00:20:00.290 --> 00:20:04.820
You might say it's fair
to have the polluter pay.

00:20:04.820 --> 00:20:08.660
But Coase's point of view is
you clean it up either way.

00:20:08.660 --> 00:20:14.480
His example was,
in fact, a train.

00:20:14.480 --> 00:20:16.820
And this was a
coal-fired steam engine

00:20:16.820 --> 00:20:19.430
running by a farmer's field.

00:20:19.430 --> 00:20:21.320
Sparks come out of
the smokestacks.

00:20:21.320 --> 00:20:23.960
Sparks start fires.

00:20:23.960 --> 00:20:26.810
The farmer can put out
the fires or the railroad

00:20:26.810 --> 00:20:29.942
can clean up the smokestack.

00:20:29.942 --> 00:20:31.400
Whoever has the
property rights are

00:20:31.400 --> 00:20:35.030
going to get the lower-cost
alternative done.

00:20:35.030 --> 00:20:38.120
STUDENT: One thing
with that scenario

00:20:38.120 --> 00:20:42.890
or with the mill scenario,
even if the mill had property

00:20:42.890 --> 00:20:45.740
rights, then wouldn't
the town want

00:20:45.740 --> 00:20:47.820
to bribe them either
way, whether or not

00:20:47.820 --> 00:20:49.070
they have the property rights?

00:20:49.070 --> 00:20:49.862
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

00:20:49.862 --> 00:20:53.570
Well, if the town
has property rights,

00:20:53.570 --> 00:20:54.800
it doesn't have to bribe.

00:20:54.800 --> 00:20:55.430
It can compel.

00:20:58.260 --> 00:21:00.420
It'll bribe if it
has no alternative.

00:21:00.420 --> 00:21:03.420
That is to say, if the mill
has the right to pollute,

00:21:03.420 --> 00:21:05.470
then it'll have to bribe.

00:21:05.470 --> 00:21:08.610
If the town has the
right, it can sue.

00:21:08.610 --> 00:21:11.780
It can compel.

00:21:11.780 --> 00:21:12.290
Yeah?

00:21:12.290 --> 00:21:14.210
STUDENT: Also assuming
the cost of damages

00:21:14.210 --> 00:21:17.100
is greater than the--

00:21:17.100 --> 00:21:22.085
the $500 is greater than the
$300, which may be true--

00:21:22.085 --> 00:21:23.210
PROFESSOR: Yeah, it could--

00:21:23.210 --> 00:21:30.140
if I make this 50,
then nobody cleans up.

00:21:30.140 --> 00:21:35.670
That's $50 worth of damages,
then the mill has the right.

00:21:35.670 --> 00:21:39.710
The town isn't going
to spend $100 or more

00:21:39.710 --> 00:21:42.800
to save itself $50
worth of damages.

00:21:42.800 --> 00:21:49.045
And if the town has
the right, well, that's

00:21:49.045 --> 00:21:50.420
actually an
interesting question.

00:21:50.420 --> 00:22:01.460
If the town has the right to
clean water, in that case,

00:22:01.460 --> 00:22:05.010
would it compel the
mill to clean up?

00:22:05.010 --> 00:22:08.040
I think you get the bargain
going the other way.

00:22:08.040 --> 00:22:09.240
You get the bargain going.

00:22:09.240 --> 00:22:11.370
You've got the right
to clean water.

00:22:11.370 --> 00:22:15.330
The mill pays them $60
to accept the damages.

00:22:15.330 --> 00:22:17.720
The mill covers the
cost of the damages

00:22:17.720 --> 00:22:19.470
because the efficient
thing, in this case,

00:22:19.470 --> 00:22:23.380
is not to clean up,
assuming this is

00:22:23.380 --> 00:22:25.780
a number that makes some sense.

00:22:25.780 --> 00:22:27.110
OK.

00:22:27.110 --> 00:22:29.250
Anything else on this?

00:22:29.250 --> 00:22:31.180
OK, why do we need EPA?

00:22:31.180 --> 00:22:32.560
Why don't we just do this?

00:22:32.560 --> 00:22:37.990
One answer is, gee, there's
an information problem

00:22:37.990 --> 00:22:39.550
in a lot of these areas.

00:22:39.550 --> 00:22:43.390
So maybe a role of government
is to do the science,

00:22:43.390 --> 00:22:45.370
tell people about it,
make sure the town knows,

00:22:45.370 --> 00:22:47.080
make sure the mill knows.

00:22:47.080 --> 00:22:49.390
Maybe even work on
clean-up technologies.

00:22:49.390 --> 00:22:52.030
All perfectly sensible things.

00:22:52.030 --> 00:22:53.670
And then assign
property rights, right?

00:22:56.550 --> 00:22:57.697
Yeah?

00:22:57.697 --> 00:22:59.280
STUDENT: It's really
