we'll come back to later

00:27:53.430 --> 00:27:59.300
in the course, which is
how come it happened?

00:27:59.300 --> 00:28:04.430
For all the years, people
worry about dirty air

00:28:04.430 --> 00:28:05.180
and dirty water.

00:28:05.180 --> 00:28:08.970
This isn't a new concern.

00:28:08.970 --> 00:28:13.880
There's a very old act that
forbids discharge of anything

00:28:13.880 --> 00:28:16.160
into the navigable waters
of the United States.

00:28:16.160 --> 00:28:19.310
It's been ignored since it was
written in the 19th century,

00:28:19.310 --> 00:28:24.840
but pollution wasn't
discovered in 1970.

00:28:24.840 --> 00:28:28.720
A Republican president signed
the Clean Air Act amendments

00:28:28.720 --> 00:28:32.790
and created EPA in 1970.

00:28:32.790 --> 00:28:35.430
And there's a historical
answer to the events

00:28:35.430 --> 00:28:36.750
that led up to it.

00:28:36.750 --> 00:28:40.140
But I'd like you to think about
the fundamental question-- is

00:28:40.140 --> 00:28:45.210
what turned the politics from
absolutely nothing going on

00:28:45.210 --> 00:28:49.260
at the federal level to a new
agency with strong mandates.

00:28:49.260 --> 00:28:50.440
Don't answer that question.

00:28:50.440 --> 00:28:53.400
We're going to do it later.

00:28:53.400 --> 00:28:54.780
You're going to say Earth Day.

00:28:54.780 --> 00:28:56.790
And I'm going to
say that's right.

00:28:56.790 --> 00:28:59.700
And then we're going to say,
where did Earth Day come from?

00:28:59.700 --> 00:29:04.290
So we've got EPA.

00:29:04.290 --> 00:29:10.730
But as the case says, I
mean, this comes down to,

00:29:10.730 --> 00:29:13.140
do policymakers like numbers?

00:29:13.140 --> 00:29:15.480
What the law said-- these
are the National Ambient Air

00:29:15.480 --> 00:29:16.350
Quality Standards.

00:29:16.350 --> 00:29:22.740
So one of EPA'S jobs
is to say, how clean

00:29:22.740 --> 00:29:26.320
must the air be everywhere
in the United States?

00:29:26.320 --> 00:29:28.850
And you could imagine doing
that in two different ways.

00:29:28.850 --> 00:29:31.870
You could imagine doing those
kinds of damage numbers,

00:29:31.870 --> 00:29:38.680
damages at different
levels of air quality,

00:29:38.680 --> 00:29:41.080
and look at the costs of
obtaining different levels

00:29:41.080 --> 00:29:43.240
of air quality.

00:29:43.240 --> 00:29:46.570
Do the maximize
benefits minus cost.

00:29:46.570 --> 00:29:49.490
What the law told
EPA to do, however,

00:29:49.490 --> 00:29:53.170
was to protect human health with
an adequate margin of safety.

00:29:56.620 --> 00:30:00.220
Why do you think they did that
as opposed to good old cost

00:30:00.220 --> 00:30:02.590
benefit analysis, which every
economist would tell them

00:30:02.590 --> 00:30:03.507
they should have done?

00:30:03.507 --> 00:30:05.920
And that law has been
in effect since 1970

00:30:05.920 --> 00:30:08.800
with every economist saying
that doesn't make any sense.

00:30:13.290 --> 00:30:15.230
Take a guess.

00:30:15.230 --> 00:30:17.090
Somebody who hasn't spoken yet.

00:30:17.090 --> 00:30:20.000
Rachel, what do you think?

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:20.750
STUDENT: Politics.

00:30:20.750 --> 00:30:21.583
PROFESSOR: Politics.

00:30:21.583 --> 00:30:23.328
But what kind of politics?

00:30:23.328 --> 00:30:25.962
STUDENT: In the sense
that the president is

00:30:25.962 --> 00:30:28.880
creating this agency that
could be in charge of this.

00:30:28.880 --> 00:30:33.363
It might be related to
the cost benefit analysis.

00:30:33.363 --> 00:30:35.030
PROFESSOR: But he has
to do an analysis.

00:30:35.030 --> 00:30:37.670
He has to protect human
health with an adequate margin

00:30:37.670 --> 00:30:38.690
of safety.

00:30:38.690 --> 00:30:40.970
And that analysis
will be challenged.

00:30:40.970 --> 00:30:42.560
It'll be challenged by industry.

00:30:42.560 --> 00:30:44.630
It'll be challenged by
the environmentalists.

00:30:44.630 --> 00:30:47.430
So you don't just
make up the numbers.

00:30:47.430 --> 00:30:49.760
You have to show that you're
protecting human health

00:30:49.760 --> 00:30:52.980
and you have to put in an
adequate margin of safety.

00:30:52.980 --> 00:30:54.230
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE] the EPA--

00:30:54.230 --> 00:30:55.313
I forget the exact number.

00:30:55.313 --> 00:30:59.290
It's like one in every
10,000 different risk factors

00:30:59.290 --> 00:31:00.290
depending on what it is.

00:31:00.290 --> 00:31:03.502
But that sounds like, oh, only
one out of every 100,000 people

00:31:03.502 --> 00:31:06.920
is going to get cancer, versus
we're saying you getting cancer

00:31:06.920 --> 00:31:09.352
is worth X amount of costs.

00:31:09.352 --> 00:31:10.810
PROFESSOR: I think
it's the optics.

00:31:10.810 --> 00:31:12.880
I think that's right.

00:31:12.880 --> 00:31:17.020
This assumes that there is some
level below which you're safe

00:31:17.020 --> 00:31:18.940
and above which you're not safe.

00:31:18.940 --> 00:31:21.430
And if we just get
away get a little bit

00:31:21.430 --> 00:31:24.660
below that low level,
we're all safe.

00:31:24.660 --> 00:31:27.180
The evidence, as far as I
know, on all these pollutants

00:31:27.180 --> 00:31:28.610
is it smooth.

00:31:28.610 --> 00:31:30.030
There is no threshold.

00:31:30.030 --> 00:31:32.880
The law presumes the threshold
because that's easier

00:31:32.880 --> 00:31:34.020
to talk about.

00:31:34.020 --> 00:31:36.330
And then, internally,
you can say, well,

00:31:36.330 --> 00:31:38.730
we'll use a one in a million
or one in 10 million,

00:31:38.730 --> 00:31:40.750
or something like that.

00:31:40.750 --> 00:31:43.920
And then you can say we're
protecting human health.

00:31:43.920 --> 00:31:47.010
You don't have to stand up
and say, valuing a human life

00:31:47.010 --> 00:31:50.010
at $6 million, dot, dot, dot.

00:31:50.010 --> 00:31:50.790
It is the optics.

00:31:50.790 --> 00:31:56.070
And I think everybody
who's thought about this

00:31:56.070 --> 00:31:58.920
understands that-- that this
is an illogical criteria.

00:31:58.920 --> 00:32:02.970
It means as you get better and
better at measuring things,

00:32:02.970 --> 00:32:06.420
you have to set tighter and
tighter standards because you

00:32:06.420 --> 00:32:11.410
detect human health effects at
lower and lower concentrations,

00:32:11.410 --> 00:32:13.380
which is not
necessarily a bad thing,

00:32:13.380 --> 00:32:17.280
but it's kind of inevitable
and kind of artificial.

00:32:17.280 --> 00:32:20.440
Why not just use a price?

00:32:20.440 --> 00:32:22.290
So why not, instead
of setting standards--

00:32:22.290 --> 00:32:26.520
this is an example from the
graph from the reading--

00:32:26.520 --> 00:32:31.720
suppose that-- and it deals
with a very simple case.

00:32:31.720 --> 00:32:33.690
Suppose that here
is the marginal cost

00:32:33.690 --> 00:32:40.480
of producing gasoline, let us
say, and there's the demand.

00:32:40.480 --> 00:32:46.950
So this would be the
equilibrium with no regulation.

00:32:46.950 --> 00:32:48.930
And Viscusi says,
well, suppose we

00:32:48.930 --> 00:32:54.600
know the damages per
gallon of gasoline produced

00:32:54.600 --> 00:32:59.130
is given by the distance
between these two curves.

00:32:59.130 --> 00:33:02.390
So we tax the
production of gasoline.

00:33:02.390 --> 00:33:04.370
Again, a simple model.

00:33:04.370 --> 00:33:06.860
We suppose that's the problem.

00:33:06.860 --> 00:33:10.550
We put a tax equal
to this amount here,

00:33:10.550 --> 00:33:13.910
then the equilibrium
is at the point where

00:33:13.910 --> 00:33:18.020
production cost plus the
marginal value of damages

00:33:18.020 --> 00:33:21.880
equals the market price.

00:33:21.880 --> 00:33:25.580
You don't want to produce
less because the total cost

00:33:25.580 --> 00:33:28.610
production plus damages
is less than the amount

00:33:28.610 --> 00:33:30.320
the market's willing to pay.

00:33:30.320 --> 00:33:33.740
You don't want to produce
more because the total cost

00:33:33.740 --> 00:33:36.920
on the margin, the total
cost for additional units,

00:33:36.920 --> 00:33:40.220
exceeds what the
market's willing to pay.

00:33:40.220 --> 00:33:44.615
So you impose the marginal
cost of damages as a price.

00:33:47.300 --> 00:33:49.170
Everything is swell.

00:33:49.170 --> 00:33:52.290
Economists are happy.

00:33:52.290 --> 00:33:56.660
And you used the price system.

00:33:56.660 --> 00:33:59.360
Why might you not
want to do that?

00:33:59.360 --> 00:34:00.770
Well, maybe you do.

00:34:00.770 --> 00:34:01.950
Why would that be hard?

00:34:01.950 --> 00:34:02.950
Let me just start there.

00:34:05.633 --> 00:34:07.675
Part of the reason you
don't do it is the optics.

00:34:10.810 --> 00:34:14.110
Again, you'd rather say we're
protecting human health than

00:34:14.110 --> 00:34:17.360
we're imposing a marginal tax
of $0.60 a gallon to reflect

00:34:17.360 --> 00:34:20.739
environmental the value
of human life lost.

00:34:20.739 --> 00:34:24.230
That's not a great headline.

00:34:24.230 --> 00:34:27.469
But suppose you could
find a way to disguise it.

00:34:27.469 --> 00:34:28.489
Suppose you just do it.

00:34:28.489 --> 00:34:29.989
This is the charge.

00:34:29.989 --> 00:34:30.860
Yeah?

00:34:30.860 --> 00:34:32.652
STUDENT: Well, if you're
going to tax, say,

00:34:32.652 --> 00:34:37.550
coal, more than you would tax
