00:34:37.550 --> 00:34:39.679
there's also reasons to
tax oil more than coal

00:34:39.679 --> 00:34:43.739
because oil's imported
and coal is domestic.

00:34:43.739 --> 00:34:45.415
So how do you--

00:34:45.415 --> 00:34:47.040
PROFESSOR: We'll do
all the arithmetic.

00:34:47.040 --> 00:34:48.750
We'll figure out
the marginal value

00:34:48.750 --> 00:34:50.850
of reduced energy security.

00:34:50.850 --> 00:34:54.840
We'll figure out the marginal
value of CO2 emissions.

00:34:54.840 --> 00:34:56.550
And we'll figure out
the marginal value

00:34:56.550 --> 00:34:59.490
of-- marginal cost, rather--
of a little bitty particulates

00:34:59.490 --> 00:35:01.005
that get in your
lung and kill you.

00:35:01.005 --> 00:35:03.505
And we'll just add them up.

00:35:03.505 --> 00:35:05.130
STUDENT: And then
you're really getting

00:35:05.130 --> 00:35:08.540
into the optics of
showing how much you're

00:35:08.540 --> 00:35:12.290
valuing a human life in
comparison to things like--

00:35:12.290 --> 00:35:15.710
PROFESSOR: Even if
you could-- well,

00:35:15.710 --> 00:35:18.350
I mean, economists
all love this.

00:35:18.350 --> 00:35:21.050
You do have the optics problem.

00:35:21.050 --> 00:35:26.000
The other problem you
got to is that's hard.

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:27.620
That's hard, right?

00:35:27.620 --> 00:35:30.980
Because you saw that range of
damages for coal-fired power

00:35:30.980 --> 00:35:34.070
plants because that
reflects where they are.

00:35:34.070 --> 00:35:36.910
So you'd want to
do this calculation

00:35:36.910 --> 00:35:40.330
at least for every
coal-fired power plant.

00:35:40.330 --> 00:35:45.680
Every gas-fired power plant,
and oh, by the way, every car.

00:35:45.680 --> 00:35:48.800
Because the damages depend on
where you drive and how far

00:35:48.800 --> 00:35:49.300
you drive.

00:35:49.300 --> 00:35:53.760
So you'd want to have
taxes for everything.

00:35:53.760 --> 00:35:58.650
Now, as an economist, that's
little short of paradise.

00:35:58.650 --> 00:36:02.910
But as a practical matter,
that's really hard.

00:36:02.910 --> 00:36:03.910
That's really hard.

00:36:03.910 --> 00:36:06.210
So what you get instead--

00:36:06.210 --> 00:36:09.750
there are prices, occasionally--
we'll talk about some systems

00:36:09.750 --> 00:36:11.810
that are price-driven--

00:36:11.810 --> 00:36:13.900
where it's easier.

00:36:13.900 --> 00:36:16.630
Suppose you're
worried about climate.

00:36:16.630 --> 00:36:20.230
Well, to a first approximation,
carbon dioxide goes in the air.

00:36:20.230 --> 00:36:21.880
Carbon dioxide mixes globally.

00:36:21.880 --> 00:36:24.470
You don't care
where it comes from.

00:36:24.470 --> 00:36:28.950
You could have a single
price for carbon dioxide.

00:36:28.950 --> 00:36:32.250
Mercury from coal-fired
power plants, the damages

00:36:32.250 --> 00:36:34.615
depend on where the plant is.

00:36:34.615 --> 00:36:36.240
So if you're going
to do prices, you're

00:36:36.240 --> 00:36:38.370
going to have to do
different prices.

00:36:38.370 --> 00:36:40.440
That's hard.

00:36:40.440 --> 00:36:44.185
Sometimes it's not
quite right that it

00:36:44.185 --> 00:36:46.560
doesn't matter where it comes
from but it's close enough.

00:36:46.560 --> 00:36:48.414
David?

00:36:48.414 --> 00:36:50.880
STUDENT: It's only really hard
