00:36:50.880 --> 00:36:52.640
So what the EPA
does now where you

00:36:52.640 --> 00:36:56.180
said they said some standard
of like, how much pollution you

00:36:56.180 --> 00:36:59.970
can put out, but they just kind
of hit the limit arbitrarily.

00:36:59.970 --> 00:37:03.830
PROFESSOR: And then--
well, they do two things.

00:37:03.830 --> 00:37:06.280
They do two things that
the case talks about.

00:37:06.280 --> 00:37:07.530
They do other things, as well.

00:37:07.530 --> 00:37:09.710
But the two things the
case talks about is they

00:37:09.710 --> 00:37:11.570
set air quality standards.

00:37:11.570 --> 00:37:14.060
And they say everywhere
in the country

00:37:14.060 --> 00:37:16.940
the air has to meet
these certain standards.

00:37:16.940 --> 00:37:20.090
Well, you could say,
gee, it makes sense

00:37:20.090 --> 00:37:21.950
to let the air be
dirty in Los Angeles

00:37:21.950 --> 00:37:24.995
because it's really hard
to clean it in Los Angeles.

00:37:24.995 --> 00:37:26.870
You can argue about
whether that makes sense.

00:37:26.870 --> 00:37:27.900
But they don't do that.

00:37:27.900 --> 00:37:30.710
The other thing they do
is they set standards

00:37:30.710 --> 00:37:35.130
and they let the states
figure out how to do that.

00:37:35.130 --> 00:37:36.660
Look, Ohio's got to be clean.

00:37:36.660 --> 00:37:38.160
Illinois has got to be clean.

00:37:38.160 --> 00:37:39.810
Figure out what to do.

00:37:39.810 --> 00:37:41.640
If you can find a
way to minimize cost,

00:37:41.640 --> 00:37:44.220
even if you want to
price stuff to do it.

00:37:44.220 --> 00:37:46.590
You, the states, figure
out how to do it.

00:37:46.590 --> 00:37:49.240
We'll check your plan to
see if it's going to work,

00:37:49.240 --> 00:37:51.510
but you give us a plan.

00:37:51.510 --> 00:37:53.460
That's not terrible.

00:37:53.460 --> 00:37:54.930
Not great, but
it's not terrible.

00:37:54.930 --> 00:37:56.790
Then the other thing they do--

00:37:56.790 --> 00:37:58.500
that the case
mentions-- is they set

00:37:58.500 --> 00:38:00.810
standards for new power plants.

00:38:00.810 --> 00:38:03.410
And those are the
same everywhere.

00:38:03.410 --> 00:38:09.060
And you can argue, yes, no,
is that the right thing to do?

00:38:09.060 --> 00:38:10.790
But it's better than
you tell me where

00:38:10.790 --> 00:38:14.450
you're going to put the
plant, I'll calculate the tax.

00:38:14.450 --> 00:38:16.250
Because that's hard.

00:38:16.250 --> 00:38:20.120
A lot of what goes
on here is you

00:38:20.120 --> 00:38:21.740
have two imperfect approaches.

00:38:21.740 --> 00:38:24.140
And I'm just saying that
while this is really

00:38:24.140 --> 00:38:26.690
a textbook ideal, it's hard.

00:38:26.690 --> 00:38:30.510
And while what EPA
actually does isn't

00:38:30.510 --> 00:38:35.300
very good from a textbook point
of view, it sort of works--

00:38:35.300 --> 00:38:36.860
particularly, the air standards.

00:38:39.980 --> 00:38:42.080
A lot of us would
say, look, Los Angeles

00:38:42.080 --> 00:38:44.200
is really hard to clean up.

00:38:44.200 --> 00:38:46.310
Let them be dirty.

00:38:46.310 --> 00:38:47.827
And of course,
that's practically

00:38:47.827 --> 00:38:49.910
what happens because it's
been impossible to clean

00:38:49.910 --> 00:38:51.860
LA to meet national standards.

00:38:51.860 --> 00:38:56.172
But at least the principle
is if you move to LA,

00:38:56.172 --> 00:38:57.380
you're entitled to clean air.

00:39:00.450 --> 00:39:03.060
So nobody's doing it perfectly.

00:39:03.060 --> 00:39:06.830
The question is, which
of the imperfect methods

00:39:06.830 --> 00:39:09.590
is A, workable
and B, reasonable?

00:39:09.590 --> 00:39:11.600
And all I'm saying
is that you don't

00:39:11.600 --> 00:39:14.330
want to get caught up
in the beauty of this

00:39:14.330 --> 00:39:18.430
without thinking about the
complexity of doing it.

