01:07:23.470 --> 01:07:24.930
This is more
political background

01:07:24.930 --> 01:07:27.030
and just one conceptual point.

01:07:27.030 --> 01:07:32.410
This is the hardest policy
problem I've ever encountered.

01:07:32.410 --> 01:07:35.170
And it's hard for a
variety of reasons.

01:07:35.170 --> 01:07:38.620
It's hard because
it's a global problem.

01:07:38.620 --> 01:07:40.900
It would require
significant actions

01:07:40.900 --> 01:07:44.630
by rich and poor countries.

01:07:44.630 --> 01:07:46.820
You saw the differences
in energy systems.

01:07:46.820 --> 01:07:48.650
All of those different
energy systems

01:07:48.650 --> 01:07:51.020
would have to do something
different over the next 20

01:07:51.020 --> 01:07:54.170
years and beyond to make a dent.

01:07:54.170 --> 01:07:57.890
And inconveniently, we
lack a world government.

01:07:57.890 --> 01:08:01.730
So if you think it's hard to
get agreement in Congress,

01:08:01.730 --> 01:08:04.400
you can pass a law,
people can be compelled.

01:08:04.400 --> 01:08:07.410
Internationally,
you can't do it.

01:08:07.410 --> 01:08:13.780
Another issue that makes it
hard is the time scales, right?

01:08:13.780 --> 01:08:16.870
Climate is an
intergenerational issue.

01:08:16.870 --> 01:08:21.350
CO2, think order of magnets--
it's not a half life,

01:08:21.350 --> 01:08:26.330
but in order of magnitude, sort
of a half-life of a century.

01:08:26.330 --> 01:08:28.700
There will be a
lot of it around.

01:08:28.700 --> 01:08:33.109
Abraham Lincoln's CO2 is
still up there, in quantity.

01:08:33.109 --> 01:08:37.279
So we would need
to do things today

01:08:37.279 --> 01:08:40.279
to benefit our
great grandchildren.

01:08:40.279 --> 01:08:42.500
This is not always an easy sell.

01:08:42.500 --> 01:08:47.510
Cost today, benefits
way down the line.

01:08:47.510 --> 01:08:50.180
And another thing that's
conceptually hard--

01:08:50.180 --> 01:08:52.910
and we're going to play with
this when we do the climate

01:08:52.910 --> 01:08:55.189
negotiation exercise--

01:08:55.189 --> 01:09:00.560
is it's hard for people to get
their head around the dynamics

01:09:00.560 --> 01:09:02.779
involved in CO2.

01:09:02.779 --> 01:09:09.290
And we'll do just a 3-minute
exercise to make this point.

01:09:09.290 --> 01:09:17.479
So I'm going to ask you
to think through what

01:09:17.479 --> 01:09:19.200
a picture would look like.

01:09:19.200 --> 01:09:23.000
So here is the
atmospheric concentration

01:09:23.000 --> 01:09:24.170
of carbon dioxide.

01:09:24.170 --> 01:09:25.970
Just imagine the scenario.

01:09:25.970 --> 01:09:31.130
It's risen up to
2000 to 2010-12.

01:09:31.130 --> 01:09:34.952
And suppose it gradually
rises and stabilizes.

01:09:34.952 --> 01:09:36.410
In fact, this is
pretty aggressive.

01:09:36.410 --> 01:09:38.939
It stabilizes at 400
parts per million,

01:09:38.939 --> 01:09:41.750
which is quite aggressive.

01:09:41.750 --> 01:09:47.450
And here is the
rate at which it's

01:09:47.450 --> 01:09:50.240
removed from the atmosphere
by natural processes.

01:09:50.240 --> 01:09:51.830
Lets just keep life simple.

01:09:51.830 --> 01:09:55.030
Suppose that rate is constant.

01:09:55.030 --> 01:09:57.750
Now, think in your
head or draw a picture.

01:09:57.750 --> 01:10:00.440
So what I gave you
there was concentration

01:10:00.440 --> 01:10:02.670
in the atmosphere.

01:10:02.670 --> 01:10:07.360
A scenario-- this is
sort of actual data.

01:10:07.360 --> 01:10:10.110
This is suppose.

01:10:10.110 --> 01:10:13.750
This is sort of actual
data for emissions.

01:10:13.750 --> 01:10:18.330
Suppose that's the rate
at which it's removed

01:10:18.330 --> 01:10:20.360
from the atmosphere, right?

01:10:20.360 --> 01:10:25.910
So this is gigatons per year.

01:10:25.910 --> 01:10:27.260
These are rates.

01:10:27.260 --> 01:10:28.708
That was a stock.

01:10:28.708 --> 01:10:29.375
These are flows.

01:10:32.850 --> 01:10:34.530
What would the
emissions path have

01:10:34.530 --> 01:10:37.500
to look like for
this graph to be

01:10:37.500 --> 01:10:40.560
consistent with the prior one?

01:10:40.560 --> 01:10:42.510
OK, don't answer.

01:10:42.510 --> 01:10:45.230
Just form an answer
in your head.

01:10:48.180 --> 01:10:48.960
Got it?

01:10:48.960 --> 01:10:49.710
Got the picture?

01:10:49.710 --> 01:10:51.830
Got the answer?

01:10:51.830 --> 01:10:53.870
It has to look like that.

01:10:53.870 --> 01:10:58.790
It has to come down to
equal removals at the end,

01:10:58.790 --> 01:11:00.990
or it doesn't stabilize.

01:11:00.990 --> 01:11:01.490
Right?

01:11:01.490 --> 01:11:04.440
Stuff coming out has to
equal stuff coming in.

01:11:04.440 --> 01:11:06.660
Water flowing into the
bathtub has to equal water

01:11:06.660 --> 01:11:08.410
flowing out of the bathtub.

01:11:08.410 --> 01:11:13.910
Now, I assume you all got this
right because you're all smart.

01:11:13.910 --> 01:11:16.720
Lots of people don't.

01:11:16.720 --> 01:11:19.420
This is a study
published in Science

01:11:19.420 --> 01:11:22.430
that used Harvard and
MIT graduate students.

01:11:22.430 --> 01:11:24.430
You guys are all smarter
than graduate students.

01:11:24.430 --> 01:11:25.360
I understand that.

01:11:28.620 --> 01:11:34.860
75% of the sample
didn't get emissions

01:11:34.860 --> 01:11:37.560
equal to removals at the end.

01:11:37.560 --> 01:11:41.680
They didn't draw a trajectory
that hit at the end.

01:11:41.680 --> 01:11:44.202
This is a little tougher,
violating conservation of mass.

01:11:44.202 --> 01:11:45.160
That's a little tricky.

01:11:45.160 --> 01:11:49.980
But over half asserted,
yeah, you can be stable.

01:11:49.980 --> 01:11:52.220
You don't have to
get to the end.

01:11:52.220 --> 01:11:54.550
You don't have to
equalize at the end.

01:11:54.550 --> 01:11:57.310
Well, these are Harvard
and MIT graduate students.

01:12:00.190 --> 01:12:04.100
Lawyers have even more
trouble with this.

01:12:04.100 --> 01:12:05.240
Nothing against lawyers.

01:12:05.240 --> 01:12:08.190
Some of them once were Harvard
and MIT graduate students.

01:12:08.190 --> 01:12:11.150
So this is missed a lot.

01:12:11.150 --> 01:12:14.360
And it's a thing that
makes the negotiation

01:12:14.360 --> 01:12:17.240
process complicated.

01:12:17.240 --> 01:12:18.950
The exercise we're
going to do here

01:12:18.950 --> 01:12:24.710
is one that's been run through
with actual negotiators

01:12:24.710 --> 01:12:29.240
with the purpose, developed here
by my colleague John Sterman,

01:12:29.240 --> 01:12:32.450
of getting them to understand
at an intuitive level

01:12:32.450 --> 01:12:36.530
the consequence
of those dynamics.

01:12:36.530 --> 01:12:40.790
For this purpose, you think of
the atmosphere as a bathtub.

01:12:40.790 --> 01:12:45.530
The height of the water in the
bathtub is the concentration.

01:12:45.530 --> 01:12:47.690
Emissions is what
comes out of the faucet

01:12:47.690 --> 01:12:50.360
and removals is what
goes down the drain.

01:12:50.360 --> 01:12:52.580
If you're worried about
local air pollution that

01:12:52.580 --> 01:12:54.740
stays in the
atmosphere for hours,

01:12:54.740 --> 01:12:56.420
you just worry about emissions.

01:12:56.420 --> 01:12:59.030
You reduce emissions
and you got it.

01:12:59.030 --> 01:13:02.810
For this problem,
that doesn't do it.

01:13:02.810 --> 01:13:07.820
A sharp cut in emissions is
consistent with the atmosphere

01:13:07.820 --> 01:13:10.980
having more and more
greenhouse gases.

01:13:10.980 --> 01:13:12.970
That's different.

01:13:12.970 --> 01:13:16.590
That complicates the problem.

01:13:16.590 --> 01:13:19.930
OK, so I'll just-- a
little more history.

01:13:19.930 --> 01:13:21.360
